French, Amos (1852 - 1923) - male

b. 23 MAR 1852

d. 1923 in Wells Co., IN

father: French, John G.(1824 - 1897)

mother: Weist, Lydia(1832 - 1895)

Amos lost his hearing at age 3, after getting scarlet fever. He entered the state institution for the deaf and dumb in Indianapolis at age 10. He met his wife Harriett at the institution, she too being deaf and a student there.

Occupation - Farmer

Burial - Six Mile Cemetery, Wells Co., IN;

spouse: Adams, Harriett A. (1852 - 1928)

- m. 14 AUG 1873

French, Charles (1811 - 1866) - male

b. 03 FEB 1811 in Oakham, MA

d. 16 JUL 1866 in Cleveland, Cuyahoga Co., OH

father: French, Isaac(1775 - 1826)

mother: Davis, Catherine(1786 - 1858)

He taught school for a short while, then attended Phillips Academy at Andover in 1834 to study for the ministry, he did not continue the study due to ill health. He took up land in Memphis, MO and after 1850 went to Memphis, MI by Prairie Schooner, where he was a merchant for 3 years. In 1853, he removed to Clevland,OH, where he was a lumber merchant the rest of his life. He held local civic offices, and Deacon of the 1st Cong. Church. He donated $5000 to the building of Oberlin College, French Hall is named in his honor.

spouse: Brakenridge, Mary Ann (1816 - 1850)

French, Ebenezer (1810 - 1880) - male

b. 12 MAY 1810 in Woodstock, VT

d. 27 FEB 1880 in Flushing, MI

father: French, Apollos(1775 - )

mother: Carpenter, Abigail

He taught school until 1834. In 1836 he started for Michigan, going over the mountains to Whitehall in a lumber wagon, then down the canal to Troy, NY; by the Erie Canal to Buffalo, and by steamer to Detroit; from there to Flushing in a lumber wagon. He settled on a farm and endured the hardships of a pioneer. He was elected to nearly all of the town offices, serving as supervisor for 7 years, and inspector of schools of Flushing.

spouse: Dunham, Martha S. (1815 - 1876)

- m. 31 AUG 1834

----------child: French, Martha (1836 - 1913)

----------child: French, Harriet E. (1838 - 1841)

----------child: French, Mary S. (1840 - 1920)

French, Edwin (1817 - 1893) - male

b. 18 JUN 1817 in Oakham, MA

d. 15 JUN 1893 in Lancaster, MO

father: French, Isaac(1775 - 1826)

mother: Davis, Catherine(1786 - 1858)

He removed before 1838 to St. Louis, MO, thence to St. Joseph, MO and later to Sand Hill, Scotland Co., MO where he was a merchant several years. He then removed to Schuyler, MO. where, in 1844 he laid out the town of Tippecanoe and was a merchant.

He went to California for two years, crossing the plains in an oxen cart, and returned via the Horn.

He laid out the town of Lancaster, MO and this is where he made his final home. He was the 1st Representative of Schuyler county to the Missouri Legislature. He served as county clerk, county treasurer, was president of Schuyler Co. National Bank and was for 40 years a Bishop in the Christian Church. From the records of Henry Dana French

spouse: Hathaway, Esther (1822 - 1903)

- m. 1843 in Schuyler, Co., MO

----------child: French, Charles Henry (1845 - 1913)

----------child: French, Wilbur Dwight (1847 - 1888)

----------child: French, Agnes M (1849 - )

----------child: French, Julia Catherine (1853 - )

----------child: French, Edwin Lewis (1856 - )

----------child: French, Alexander Campbell (1858 - 1860)

----------child: French, Mary Ella (1861 - 1862)

French, Henry (1813 - 1884) - male

b. 23 JAN 1813 in Woodstock, VT

d. 04 OCT 1884 in Flushing, MI

father: French, Apollos(1775 - )

mother: Carpenter, Abigail

He was bound out at the age of 15 yrs. to Tracy Bingham and lived with him until 21 years of age. He then traveled to the west with his brother, Ira, going by wagon and canal to Albany, rail to Schenectady; canal to Buffalo, and by steamer to Detroit. After one nights stay in that town he set out with his party and reached Flint, MI about Oct 18, 1835. He was the Town Treasurer for Flushing, MI, where he was a well to do and much respected citizen.

spouse: Ensign, Marie Abigail (1813 - 1871)

- m. 25 NOV 1835 in Flushing, MI

He was twice elected to the Legislature in Mass. in 1835 and 1841. Was a member of the Common Council of Fall River for several years, also assessor. French, John (~1600 - 1646) - male

b. ABT 1600

d. 1645/6 in Cambridge, MA

HISTORY

John French, may have been born in England, he probably came with his wife to America about 1635, settling in Cambridge, MA. He did not immigrate with his brother, William French. We do not know where either John or William were born, nor do we know the names of their parents. In 1637 he was listed as a property owner, and in 1642, was on a list of proprietors of Cambridge. He is mentioned in church records, 1638-39-40. By trade he was a tailor. Both he and his wife died during an epidemic in the winter of 1645/6 leaving five children: Mary, John, Sarah, Joseph and Nathaniel; the oldest was11 years old and the youngest 2. Another family tradition has it that he was killed by an arrow while standing in his doorway eating an ear of corn. The children were brought up by his brother, Lt. William French (Chart #2) who first lived in Cambridge, then moved to Billerica, MA, about 1654 where 30 acres in this new settlement had been set apart on Jun 9, 1652 for these five orphans.1

The baptism of all five children is indicated in the Cambridge, MA Vital Records (First Congregational Church) but no dates are included Source: The Hartland French Family, compiled by Rev. Hollis M. French, 1968, submitted by FFA member Vernon French.

Occupation - Tailor

Burial - 16 FEB 1645/6; Cambridge, MA;

spouse: �, Sarah (? - ~1635)

spouse: �, Joanna (? - 1646)

- m. ABT 1635

----------child: French, Mary

----------child: French, Sarah (1637 - 1710)

----------child: French, John (? - 1646)

----------child: French, Joseph (1640 - 1694)

----------child: French, Nathaniel (1643 - 1711)

French, Joseph (1640 - 1694) - male

b. 04 APR 1640 in Probably Cambridge, MA

d. 1694 in Taunton, MA

father: French, John(~1600 - 1646)

mother: �, Joanna(? - 1646)

Joseph moved between 1678 and 1680 to the southern part Taunton, which became Berkley in 1735, and took land next to James Phillips, Richard Burt and Elkanah Babbit. Here his last four children were born. His will dated 24 April 1694, mentions the following children: Joseph, John, Nathaniel, Jacob, Ebenezer, Jonathan, Elizabeth, wife of Jas. Phillips; his wife Experience was the executrix of the will.

Joseph saw active service in King Phillip's War in 1675, was a member of the 4th Sq. 1st Military Co. of Taunton, in 1682, and was listed in the inspection return of King William's War of 1691.

French, Joseph (1766 - 1845) - male

b. 03 JUN 1766 in Berkley, MA

d. 20 MAR 1845 in French Twp., Adams Co., IN

father: French, Jacob(1738 - 1783)

mother: Richmond, Wealthy(1738 - >1790)

We aren't quite sure when Joseph left Massachusetts, but it appears to have been after Eunice died in 1795. I have a copy of a deed of sale dated, October 1st, 1798, for purchase of land it said that Joseph was of Hamilton in the County of Chenango (NY). The land was being purchased from Benjamin Walker of the City of New York. The next place we find them living was in Eaton, Madison County, and living next door to them were Eunice's parents. Madison County was formed from Chenago County in 1806. Joseph appeared to have owned a considerable amount of land in Madison County.

In 1835 Joseph moved with son Joseph Jr. to what is now French Twp, in Adams County. They built cabins and planted corn and vegetables. Joseph Sr. then rode back to New York to get his family. They were accompanied on the trip by the Haughton, Morrow and Dunbar Families. All of Joseph and Sally's children followed them there, except for Jacob. In those days the area was heavily wooded and there were bears and deer in the forest. It was said that there were many species of trees, one being yellow poplar, which in now extinct.

Joseph had large land tracks in Adams County, and he took an active interest in the community. It is said that French Twp. where they resided was named for him. There was also the Lot French family, who also resided in the area. They came from Ohio, and it was said that they were not related to our French family.

It was said that Joseph served in the War of 1812, probably in a NY regiment. His military coat, was passed down to his son George, who passed it down to his son, Jay George and then it went to his son Eugene. Eugene's daughter Olive gave the coat to the museum in Ft. Wayne, IN.

Occupation - Farmer, Silversmith

Burial - French Cemetery, French Twp, Adams Co.;

spouse: Mills, Eunice (1772 - 1795)

- m. 1793

----------child: French, Joseph (1794 - 1842)

spouse: Smith, Sally (1776 - 1843)

- m. FEB 1797 in MA

----------child: French, Eunice (1798 - 1839)

French, Leonard V. (1868 - 1941) - male

Leonard never married. It was said by his sisters he had his father's trunk, which contained his father's diary, old books and other family momentous. Apparently, he was very spiteful towards his sisters, and told them he was going to burn the trunk. Fortunately part of his father's diary has survived, but one wonders what else the trunk might have contained. He lived with his parents until his mother's death then returned to Wells County, IN.

French, Lewis Seymore (1816 - ) - male

b. 04 JUL 1816 in Barnard, VT

father: French, Roger(1760 - 1850)

mother: Tobey, Achsah(? - 1853)

At age 25, he shipped for 3 years on a whaling vessel in the Pacific. The boat ran short of water and they were obligated to drink rainwater caught in newly painted boats. The crew were poisoned by the lead, and some died. Lewis was put ashore on a south sea island, later going to a hospital in Chile. When homeward bound, he became ill and was put ashore. He later returned to Vermont, but was never able to do hard work as the result of his illness. He kept a store at the outlet of the lake and was postmaster for 40 yrs from 1857

Occupation - Town Clerk 1870-1892

spouse: Swift, Charlotte F.

- m. 01 JAN 1850

----------child: French, Edward T. (1850 - 1894)

----------child: French, Rollin S. (1854 - 1858)

 

French, Lieut. Asa (1740 - 1832) - male

b. 28 OCT 1740 in Berkley, MA

d. 03 DEC 1832 in Oakham, MA

father: French, John(1700 - 1794)

mother: �, Marcy(? - 1787)

He came to Middleboro, MA in 1750 withhis parents. Was a private in Capt Benjamin Prat's Co., and served in the French and Indian War in the campaign in and about Fort Henry, 1757. In 1768 he purchased land in Oakham, MA and made his home there in 1769. He was elected 2nd Lt. 14 May 1776, of the 8th (Oakham) Co. when the 4th Worcester Co. Regt. of MA Militia was organized at Brookfield. He was commissioned 31 May 1776. Served 3 yrs in Rev. War as Lt. in Capt. Crawford's Co. Aft war taught school, was Selectman of Oakham MORE

spouse: Smith, Susanna Annie (1745 - 1802)

- m. 24 OCT 1765

French, Samuel (1777 - 1861) - male

b. 23 FEB 1777 in Berkley, Bristol Co., MA

d. 05 MAR 1861 in Berkley, Bristol Co., MA

father: French, Samuel(1751 - 1830)

mother: Pierce, Lucy(? - 1845)

He was a sea captain for many years and visited many countries including the West Indies and the South Sea Islands. He could speak 17 languages and was able to communicate with the various races and tribes whom he encountered. He was more than once attacked by pirates, but escaped unharmed and was once captured by a Portuguese man-of-war, but his ability to communicate with officers of the vessel insured his release. He spent his last years on shore, perhaps in Ohio.
